04439nam a22005535i 9780226072692DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20132013ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a2013013420  a97802260726927 a10.7208/97802260726922doi  a(DE-B1597)523982  a(OCoLC)861692045  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL00aBQ709.R85bB87834 2013 7aSOC0000002bisacsh1 aBernstein, Anya, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aReligious Bodies Politic :bRituals of Sovereignty in Buryat Buddhism /cAnya Bernstein. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2013] 4c©2013  a1 online resource (272 p.) :b27 halftones, 6 tables  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aBuddhism and Modernity00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tA Note on Transliteration -- tChronology of Events -- tIntroduction -- t1. Pilgrims, Fieldworkers, and Secret Agents: Buryat Buddhologists and a Eurasian Imaginary -- t2. Sovereign Bodies: Death, Reincarnation, and Border Crossings in the Transnational Terrain -- t3. The Post-Soviet Treasure Hunt: New Sacred Histories and Geographies -- t4. Disciplining the Monastic Body: Buryat Monks and Nuns -- t5. The Body As Gift: Gender, the Dead, and Exchange in the Chöd Ritual Economy -- t6 Buddhism after Socialism: Money and Morality in the World of Saṃsāra -- tEpilogue: Bodies, Gifts, and Sovereignty -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aReligious Bodies Politic examines the complex relationship between transnational religion and politics through the lens of one cosmopolitan community in Siberia: Buryats, who live in a semiautonomous republic within Russia with a large Buddhist population. Looking at religious transformation among Buryats across changing political economies, Anya Bernstein argues that under conditions of rapid social change—such as those that accompanied the Russian Revolution, the Cold War, and the fall of the Soviet Union—Buryats have used Buddhist “body politics” to articulate their relationship not only with the Russian state, but also with the larger Buddhist world. During these periods, Bernstein shows, certain people and their bodies became key sites through which Buryats conformed to and challenged Russian political rule. She presents particular cases of these emblematic bodies—dead bodies of famous monks, temporary bodies of reincarnated lamas, ascetic and celibate bodies of Buddhist monastics, and dismembered bodies of lay disciples given as imaginary gifts to spirits—to investigate the specific ways in which religion and politics have intersected. Contributing to the growing literature on postsocialism and studies of sovereignty that focus on the body, Religious Bodies Politic is a fascinating illustration of how this community employed Buddhism to adapt to key moments of political change.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aBuddhismzRussia (Federation)zBuri︠a︡tii︠a︡. 0aBuddhist monasticism and religious orderszRussia (Federation)zBuri︠a︡tii︠a︡. 0aBuriatsxReligion. 0aEurasian schoolxReligious aspectsxBuddhism. 0aMonastic and religious life (Buddhism)zRussia (Federation)zBuri︠a︡tii︠a︡. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311063538640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226072692423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780226072692.jpg  a978-3-11-063538-6  University of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles